The UK’s reliance on Visa and Mastercard for the vast majority of card transactions highlights a deeper issue: strategic dependence on foreign-owned payment infrastructure.  

As money becomes digital infrastructure, control over payment rails is becoming as critical as control over energy or telecommunications. Without domestic alternatives for stablecoins, tokenised assets and instant settlement, future financial systems may default to external control.  

The broader implication extends beyond the UK. Nations that fail to build their own financial rails risk losing influence over the next generation of digital capital markets. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}  

